      "date": "2014-03-29 02:35:02.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nShadow Autotest has started the test process",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "879a11cba1ef18fd8b6e481e4229b901295c7216",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2014-03-29 09:27:28.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nTests received by maloo, run on el6/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/556fd2c0-b724-11e3-98de-52540035b04c).  Ran 1 tests.  1 tests failed: node-provisioning-1.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "247fda0d9e33bcd3ce026d0beece12fcb8caa449",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-03-29 22:48:35.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nZFS is slow enough by itself without adding a full txg sync every time an iterator is used.  This seems like a pretty major performance hit for a very marginal condition. \n\nThe first question is whether it is necessary for LFSCK to iterate over an object that was just allocated?  I think it would be better to just skip new objects, as is done in a few places in the code already. If the sanity-lfsck or sanity-scrub test needs the sync to work properly, then this may be one of the few cases where I would advise changing the test to add a sync.  LFSCK is intended to fix long-standing problems and should not spend complexity to fix transient non-issues. \n\nThat seems racy in any case, so it would be better to ignore such objects. If we really need to iterate this object, is it possible to only sync that object if it is being iterated?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "b99cd1d25f23ec12f7b91c2aee2c31524e8128b7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2014-03-30 02:05:32.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nTests received by maloo, run on el6/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/c3a394e4-b7af-11e3-98de-52540035b04c).  Ran 1 tests.  1 tests failed: node-provisioning-1.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "d8090c2bc763a2ff06e92f8afdc79faca00115db",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2014-03-30 11:31:33.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nthe change adds a sync to the iterator initialization only, so when LFSCK starts that would cause a sync. I'd think this isn't the worst thing to happen. having that said, I agree that it is still racy and not helpful for real LFSCK. in the initial patch (not pushed though) I did use sync;sleep in sanity-lfsck/16b, but then realized that it's probably easier to do sync in one place. I'm discussing the root issue with Brian, probably we'll find a better solution (compared to sync in the code/tests).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "9e4ba06b02da907d733abf833585fdc688d79f28",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-03-31 15:39:21.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nIf this is just for the LFSCK iterator then I don't mind it. That should only be called rarely. If objects appear after iteration starts it is fine if they are skipped.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
